<br>
The tangibility issue is irrelevant; while you may personally choose to place little or no value on something because it is intangible, that has no bearing on it's legal status or the value that others place on it.  For example, if I uploaded the entire Everquest client to a server of my own and allowed others to download it for free, that would be illegal.  I wouldn't be stealing a tangible item, no disks changed hands and VI didn't actually lose any physical items.  However, I would still be considered to have broken the law.  The folks at VI or in the court wouldn't care about whether I choose to value the EQ client program or not, they do.  It's legal status is completely independent of it's tangibility or lack thereof. <p>Erevan MacQuaide, cleric of Nimue <BR>
