<br>
A can of coke has an absoloute value<br>
A 60th Warrior has an implied value<br>
<br>
As others have pointed out, the fact that characters change hands for real currency, and the fact that a market exists for these characters, gives them value.<br>
<br>
Value can also be tied to work or effort.  Now if you work as a coder and produce programs for your employer then the employer will (unless your contract states otherwise and barring any country specific anomalies) retain intellectual property rights to that code. <br>
<br>
To those who say the chars have no value you may want to consider the EULA for EQ, legally its very difficult to prove ownership on something that has no value and yet Verant state that the account and characters belong to them, this implies that both have value.<br>
<br>
Every test you can oput against an EQ account deems it to have a material value to either Verant and/or the acount holder and to other people who may wish to buy it.<br>
<br>
While the game is virtual the time spent on it is not, and as we all know, time = money.<br>
<br>
Consider share trading.  Time is spent selling and buying (and researching) small bits of companies and while the shares have an implicit value at a set time, try taking your share certificate to the company in question and demanding its worth in real currency.<br>
<br>
Time is the most valuable commodity we have (imho), hence the phrase 'spending' time, in that we purchase 'goods/services' with our time.<br>
